When I got the results I was so shocked by what they revealed. My spine had been misaligned for so long that my disks were already wearing off, specially those in my neck which would explain the neck pain. < Text>
This is a must stop shop for anyone visiting Old Town. Every time we visit San Diego, we make a point of stopping in and watching the staff hand spin, stretch and package taffy - it's very cool and you can't stop watching. On top of that, there's a huge variety of other candies and treats, many which you don't see everywhere. A cool stop for anyone who loves candy, that's for sure.</Text>

< rate>
1<//rate>
< Review>
i've been a customer of this shop for about 18 years.  this review is for their service department.

i had a brand new made to order steel frame that needed a chris king bottom bracket installed.  the BB has a large cup size (threadfit 30) that requires a special tool....one that i didn't have at the time.  they charged me $30 for the install.

i built my bike up and got half way up Emma.  i heard the creaking and grinding from the BB and also started to feel it through the pedals.  it was focking horrible and cringe inducing.  i stopped to examine and found that both of the BB cups were loose.  now of course i felt the cups before i continued my build, but with not having the tool, i couldn't really test it.  i trusted the bike trip to install the $200 bottom bracket to spec....with 40 Nm of torque.  clearly that didn't happen.  now i'm wondering if my brand new bottom bracket's bearings are now also toast.

in the past, i've known all the service managers and wrenches and felt very confident in the level of skill and care provided to my bikes.  that is no longer the case.  i don't think i'll let anyone from there touch my bikes again unless Nate or old Phil come back.  it's a shame too cause they are my closest bike shop.

bu hao< /Review>

< Review>
This review will receive only one star which I feel is 1 too many.  On presidents day I called to find out whether I could have two tires put on my bike. I was told "no problem, come on in. It will cost $15 per wheel." When I arrived the 1st thing that came out of the mechanics mouth was "do you have an appointment".  I explained to him that I had called just a few minutes earlier and was told that there would be no problem. He asked who did I speak with. I said I believe his name was Mike. He said there is no Mike that works here. At that point an individual from the shop walks over to asked a question and was referred to as Mikey.  Reluctantly,  upon realizing that I heard him say Mikey instead of Mike he decided to work on my bike .  After removing both wheels and the old tires I had on the bike he opened up the package that I had given to him only to realize that they were the wrong size. I agreed to buy a pair of tires from him after realizing my error. Moments later another individual and his 2 sons approached the same counter and asked if they too could have their new tires put on their bike that were not purchased from their store.They were not asked if they had an appointment, making me feel, as a black man,   uncomfortable, to say the least. When he completed my job I was taken to the front desk to pay.  To my surprise I was being charged $20 per tire. When I pointed out that I was quoted it would be $15 per tire, the excuse was that because I have an E bike they had to remove numerous wires to install the tires. I pointed out to him that my bike  was a mid drive meaning simply that there were no wires to remove and that the  wheels on my bike would be no different than any other bicycle to remove and replace.  Reluctantly  he gave me the benefit of the doubt and charged me $15 per tire as agreed upon originally. I even pointed out to him that I purchased the tires from his store.  Given my experience I would not recommend this store to anyone<//Review>

< review>
I had a bad experience here recently. I changed the pads on my hydraulic brake system and accidentally allowed some air in to the closed system. I didn't have the proper bleed kit and I had never bled bike brakes before, so I took it to the Bicycle Trip where I had been to before without any complaints. I asked them to bleed the rear brake system and they said it would be done by the end of the day if they were able to do a simple (I think they said lever bleed). At the end of the day they said they needed to keep it over night because it needed a more comprehensive block bleed. I agreed, stating that I wanted the job done right. They had my bike all of the next day, and just before closing I went to pick my bike up. The mechanic told me that they couldn't get all of the air out of the system due to too many adapters which have a tendency to trap air in hard to bleed pockets. They still charged me $30 and said there was nothing more they could do. Let's think about this for a second. How is it that they couldn't bleed my system properly? When I got the bike new 10/2018 everything was perfect, so obviously a proper brake bleed was not impossible to accomplish. They claimed that it wasn't their fault because I was the one who changed the brake pads. Well they admitted to me that they had sanded the brake pads as part of the job, but the pads were literally brand new. I had installed them the night before. So when I got my bike back, after two days for a simple rear brake bleed I couldn't even lock the rear wheel up to skid. They never should have sanded the 1 day old brake pads, and they admittedly couldn't even bleed the brakes correctly. I ended up replacing the pads again, and the brakes work well enough to skid, but the brake lever is still "mushy" due to an incomplete $30 job that they admitted they couldn't fully bleed correctly. Why charge me if they can't do the job, and in the process they also cost me another $10 for new pads. In conclusion, I bought new pads and even though the brake lever is a little mushy, I can once again skid to a stop if needed. I'm buying a bleed kit from amazon and I'm pretty confident that I'll be able to bleed the system better than the $30 job that they did poorly. I will admit that a week later I went in there a bit drunk and called them out on their piss-poor work and got myself kicked out. I had that coming, but they have this review coming because if they had done the job right, or simply said they were incapable and not charged me then everything would be fine with me. They shouldn't say they weren't able to do the job properly and still take my money. I took it to a shop to have it done right, gave them all the time they needed, and they took my my money after they failed to complete the job.<//review>

This is a great bicycle shop. I have purchased several bikes from them over the years and have all of my repair work done in their shop. Prices are competitive and there is reasonable variety in their stock for a medium-sized store. The repair people are prompt and give accurate time estimates for the work. I have had nothing but good experiences here.</Review>

<rating>2< /rating><text>I Brought my bike in to have the brakes adjusted, because they where squeaking and when I returned to pick it up it was obvious at a glance that the breaks where installed incorrectly and would squeal horribly. They where set at well more than a 15 degree angle to the rim so that only one edge could ever touch the rim.  To make things worse the rear breaks where angled the wrong direction! Cantilever Breaks are supposed to be installed with a slight angle so that as the break grips it pulls the trailing edge toward the rim allowing the full pad to be used, these breaks where installed to that only the very edge of the pad could ever be used preventing anything close to full effectiveness of the breaks

When I rode back into the store from the test ride the breaks where so loud the other customers had to cover their ears. After they took another shot at adjusting them and putting different breaks pads on the result of the second test ride was exactly the same, and ear splitting squeal. The second star in this review comes from the fact that the third test the breaks only squeaked very slightly at the very end of a stop, which is acceptable.

When I have adjusted the same breaks in the past my self (which took a couple hours to get right) they worked fine, I took it in this time to same my self the time and instead had to sit in the store for an hour so I lost both the time and money.

While in the process of fixing the breaks, for no reason I can tell, they unmounted my front light and put it back on pointing about 30 degrees to the right and hanging down with a really poorly done tape job? They agreed not to charge me for the break pads by way of compensation which, although annoying, does show willingness to correct mistakes.

This shop seems well suited to buying new bikes and they have perfectly good prices on parts, though I can only recommend avoiding them for repairs.</text>< Resp>

Arthur Ulfeldt</name>
<Time>1381772677322<//Time><rating>2< /rating>< Text>
I Brought my bike in to have the brakes adjusted, because they where squeaking and when I returned to pick it up it was obvious at a glance that the breaks where installed incorrectly and would squeal horribly. They where set at well more than a 15 degree angle to the rim so that only one edge could ever touch the rim.  To make things worse the rear breaks where angled the wrong direction! Cantilever Breaks are supposed to be installed with a slight angle so that as the break grips it pulls the trailing edge toward the rim allowing the full pad to be used, these breaks where installed to that only the very edge of the pad could ever be used preventing anything close to full effectiveness of the breaks

When I rode back into the store from the test ride the breaks where so loud the other customers had to cover their ears. After they took another shot at adjusting them and putting different breaks pads on the result of the second test ride was exactly the same, and ear splitting squeal. The second star in this review comes from the fact that the third test the breaks only squeaked very slightly at the very end of a stop, which is acceptable.

When I have adjusted the same breaks in the past my self (which took a couple hours to get right) they worked fine, I took it in this time to same my self the time and instead had to sit in the store for an hour so I lost both the time and money.

While in the process of fixing the breaks, for no reason I can tell, they unmounted my front light and put it back on pointing about 30 degrees to the right and hanging down with a really poorly done tape job? They agreed not to charge me for the break pads by way of compensation which, although annoying, does show willingness to correct mistakes.

This shop seems well suited to buying new bikes and they have perfectly good prices on parts, though I can only recommend avoiding them for repairs.</Text>

<Time>1480215065995<//Time>< rating>
4</rating>
< Text>
This particular Du-par's is very nostalgic because it is located right near Hollywood.  Celebrities come in occasionally and it has been here since 1938.  It was especially fun for my husband and I to visit this past early morning Black Friday 2016, because we hadn't been there since 1982 after just seeing E.T. at a nearby theatre.  I do have to say, that the only reason I am giving it a 4 star, my tri-tip dinner plate was not as good as the Du-par's in Pasadena.  The meat was definitely over cooked. Their pancakes were outstanding as usual, but my dinner was not that great.</Text>

< Review>
Good home style food served here with lousy service. I've never hear a bad plate here except for this muffin but the service is the worst. 1509996038451< /Date>
<text>Du-par's Restaurant & Bakery, Studio City, California

A friend had actually taken ME there almost two (2) weeks ago and I really enjoyed their food.

I therefore decided to return back there last weekend and had a Very Enjoyable Dining Experience!

For Lunch:  I had USDA Prime New York Steak, along with a Garden Salad, Fresh Squeezed Orange Juice since that is one of My Favorite Juices with a very Delicious Strawberry Cream Pie for Dessert.

During my Dining Room experience I also had the opportunity to meet Drew Carey who was enjoying his Lunch there as well and so You Never Know Who You Are Going To Meet at Du-par's Restaurant & Bakery!

I was very much Impressed with the Food and the Service received by Walter, one of their Lead Waiters who has been with the restaurant for a very long time!

I want to personally Thank Frances Tario for Inviting ME back to the restaurant and Walter, the Lead Waiter for providing ME with Fantastic, Top Notch Du-Par's Restaurant & Bakery Dining Services and for Helping Me Make My Youtube Video back on Saturday, November 4, 2017.

Sincerely yours,

Howard Paul Shore
Visitor
Executive, Volunteer Writer For Google And Tripadvisor Websites

< Text>
Du-pars is a mainstay of Studio City.  I grew up going there on many Sundays.  To this day I still come because the food is good and reasonably priced.  The parking lot can be very busy due to the shopping center, so get there a few minutes early if you are meeting someone at peak hours.  try it, I think you will like it if you like diners.<//Text>

<review>What began as a minor love affair where I would stop between clients when I needed a quick coffee and bite, soon evolved into a strong relationship where I relinquished my avalanching Starbucks addiction. Little Ground Cafe has found its strength in not just top notch coffee, or delicious seasonal food items, but within the heart of it's staff which both sees efficiency and genuine kindness. If it is your first time may I recommend a latte and a pastry, or maybe a Pulled Pork Burrito if you are running out the house and skipped breakfast. Lunch? No problem! This cafe has a variety of different consistent options as well as three to four seasonal options to meet your palettes standard. One thing is for sure...I love Little Ground!</review><Name>Quenten Millhauser< /Name><Rate>5< /Rate></record>

< time>
1486411456613< /time>
<Rate>4</Rate>< Text>
This section of Flower Street is dominated by private commercial property (namely film studio offices), so Little Ground is a welcome addition to an otherwise homogeneous area. For anyone working in the vicinity, it's a great way to take a break and stretch your legs on break, or provide a nice change of venue for a quick, small meeting.

Wifi is available and free. Parking can be tricky -- there is temporary parking directly out front, but anyone looking to sit down will probably want to seek out curb on one of the residential side streets. Bicycling would be a great choice; there is dedicated bike lane on the stretch of Sonora leading up to the shop.

All of Little Ground's seating is outdoor, but well-shielded from the noise of traffic by walls, and from beating sun by canopy. My main regret is that they're not open on weekends -- I realize the bulk of their business comes from the Monday through Friday working crowd, but that patio would be a fantastic place to hole up with a laptop on a Saturday afternoon!<//Text>

<Review>My wife and I have had many procedures done at The Smile Artists and we've never had a bad experience. We both had whitening done before our wedding (which looked great), fillings, and both deep and regular cleanings with many of the hygienists. Dr. Assudani fixed a tooth I chipped and the result is indistinguishable from the original.

My most recent procedure was wisdom teeth removal by Dr. Masood and it was about as close to enjoyable as having teeth removed is likely to get.

Finally, the patient experience is not complete without a great administrative experience and Jackie at the front desk is the best. She's helpful and friendly and even willing to help breakdown dental insurance choices when the time comes to enroll.

Their practices during the pandemic have been top-notch too- limited exposure to other patients, temperature checks, futuristic-looking helmet protection for their staff and new equipment in all the rooms to mitigate risks. Obviously dental work seems like one of the riskiest things to do during the pandemic but I felt comfortable and safe the entire time, and also important, I think their staff were just as well protected.

Overall The Smile Artists is the best dentist I've had and even though we moved from the area we'll keep returning in the future.< /Review>< pics>

<rating>4<//rating><Text>Westfield is a larger mall with many more businesses than the Metreon, but the Metreon movie theatre is San Francisco's best bet for flick fanfare but the big Target right around the corner has become the real main attraction here, in the Age of COVID. When it seemed like the American shopping experience was becoming an endangered species during the most desperate months of 2020, Target kept it's doors open. And thank heavens. Without them, the shopping and dining experience in downtown SF would have become monopolized by Walgreens. And that's not a world I want to live in. No offense, Walgreens. <rating>3<//rating><Review>The Metreon used to be an awesome place. Mostly due to the presence of the ONLY Playstation Store in United States. That one store made the entire mall a blast. Paired with an IMAX theater and adequate chain restaurants, it was hard to have a bad time there.

Nowadays, it is a husk of its former self - a painfully obvious reminder of the gentrification that plauges SF. Target, Chipotle, Starbucks and a cookie cutter food court leave much to be desired by anyone who remembers the days of rows of Playstations and countless hours spent playing there.

The Metreon is probably much better off financially with all of the stores and renovations that exist now, though I can't help but yearn for the good old times...<//Review>< pics>

< Text>
Shopping in the middle of a busy, congested city can be a pain, and there are a handful of other places to shop nearby, but the Metreon is the spot. Easy to swing into Target or grab a bite to eat on the move. Easily accessible and there is parking nearby thanks to the Moscone Center.< /Text>

<Name>Christopher Tozzi<//Name><Date>1556694873116</Date><rate>5< /rate><review>Since it opened it 1999 I've gone to the Metreon. My fave park in the city for a long time is right outside the Metreon doors and has views of the old church and waterfalls with the city in the back and is truly beautiful. Inside best movie theater in SF with IMAX. Good food selection downstairs located both in and outside the building, but we usually eat across the street at Tropisueno(great Mexican food and drinks)! Also there is a small Target here for random stuff, the entire building in and out is fairly clean, and overall I just like this place. Walk here but driving will cost ya. Mission st parking across the street is your safest and  easiest place to find parking. < review>
Went here to watch Star Wars in Dolby... so awesome!  I love the Metreon theater for the amenities and the seats are so comfortable.

I also like the various food outlets at the Metreon. I've tried Inay's Kitchen and it's pretty decent Filipino food. My husband and I tried Cafe-X just to see how the robot operates and makes coffee. It was pretty cool and the coffee came out pretty good.  It's a bit pricey, equivalent to a venti SB drink but the actual size is like an SB grande.</review>

Went to see Pet Semetary (sic) once again, the theater is amazing. I love bass that shakes the seat. The movie so-so, but there is just something about movies, popcorn and chocolate covered raisins. <Text>I'm just not a Mall person, but- the Metreon isn't "too much". The Target store still amazes me, it's huge and has good stuff at a decent price. I go there sometimes three times a month. There is a Starbucks and it has plenty of places to sit and people watch, also it's not as crowded as you might expect. I have only been to the movies here once. I'm a big movie person, and even though the theaters have stadium seating, great sound, (Very loud) and special events it's almost phrohibitively expensive. Especially if you are coming with your family. With admission, snacks, parking, and depending on how far you came, it adds up. Oh, there's a 3D theater, but I haven't been. < review>
This is my theater of choice for watching movies in IMAX/3D. It dates back to when IMAX was a ginormous 70mm film reel in the lobby.

There's parking fairly close, and not much of a gauntlet of homeless on the way. One of my few reasons to venture into SF.</review>

Love, love, love this place! Great theater location, it's by an ice skating center, a Target, a Super Duper burger place and a ton of other restaurants.

<Pictures>None</Pictures>< review>
It's 1947 and a loud boom awakens the residents of San Francisco at 315am.A metal ship from another world had plumetted into ours and smack dab into a shopping district. As people ran closer to see what the ruckus was, people could hear the piercing cry of a child. A child indeed was at the center of this crash, and yes the child was shrieking, but miraculously unhurt.
And it was here that Metreon was born and introduced to the world. Abonded by parents who realized his homeworld was going to end. Metreon was raised hy humble San Franciscans.The child was taised to be fair and righteous and grew stronger and realized he possessed abilities.
To honor the great Metreon, this mall was built upon the sacred land upon which the ship had landed. Come and enjoy a bowl of Metreon Soup or some yummy Metreon Mango Ice Cream!< /review>

<user_id>105341443160698699104<//user_id><rating>5</rating>< Text>
This is where you can find on the second floor one of the only two full-scale Targets in San Francisco. There is also the AMC Theatres on the third floor. There is one IMAX screen and 15 other standard/3D screens where you can see the latest films. There are also a multitude of great dining choices on the first floor including but not limited to Chipotle, Super Duper Burgers, Buckhorn Steakhouse, a thai restaurant, and several other great places to eat.</Text>

<Review>Ideally located in the heart of downtown San Francisco and minutes away from both bart and shopping venue...it is quite the gem. The bottom floor where the ticket kiosk are found...there is are an array of dining options to choose from especially for those that are hoping to skip the whole popcorn and sugar induced collar drinks. From Korean to Filipino to Thai and American...you have a decent choice option for a healthy meal. For those that need to get their fill of bubble drinks... you're in luck as they have one stationed directly across from the ticket kiosk. For anyone with children, cupcakes and ice cream can be found from the creamery shop. Just located next door you have even more options to choose from and the future ramen shop is set to schedule for opening any time soon. Alright let get to the good stuff. The metreon usually carries the newest movie release and not only that. They also have the biggest it not the second biggest IMAX screen in the bay area! The size of their competition are so generic that you have you taking for a ticket refund! For that that want even more immersive experience. They have a Dolby digital screen as well. It's comparable to the IMAX but the sounds pushed furthermore. What I do like about this place is that they also showcase international film as well.<//Review></record>

< Review>
I've visited the Metreon many times over the years and watched it's tenants come and go. At times it has more restaurants or better stores (like when it had the Sony flagship store). And sometimes they experiment with things, like a farmers market at one point. Today it seems to have a modest balance. The main attractions here now are Target and the AMC movie theater.

I do like some of the places on the outside like Split and Chipotle. The access to the Yerba Buena Garden is also nice when the weather is good.</Review>

<Rating>4<//Rating>< Text>
Definitely a good perk to live within walking distance to this place. Very convenient on a regular basis to be close to a high quality food court, movie theater, and shops surrounded by grassy spaces - hard to find in San Fran!  In addition, the new city target has made it so much easy to find groceries and alcohol at a reasonable price instead of spending a ton at convenience stores.  Check for events on top of the Metreon as well - they have large ballroom spaces at the top with outdoor balconies for nice views of the skyline!</Text>

</dataset><record>
<UserId.>115817965208025763481< /UserId.><Name>I Am Everywhere< /Name><date>1543893990990</date>< rate>
4<//rate>
<Text>Overall, the Metreon is generally a pleasant place to go. Credit the adjacent Yerba Buena Gardens with is beautiful landscaping and calming waterfall.  The Metreon offers a variety of eats including a Buckhorn Grill and is anchored by a City Target and a Theater complex.  And, what would it be without a Starbucks.  Located on the corner of Mission street and 4th street, it's always humming with customers.  Of note is the paid public parking across 4th street which is highly recommended over the almost nonexistent parking.  It also has a ballroom available for special occasions which can be rented if available.  It's often booked so is best to call well in advance to get a reservation.  Just one block from there is the Westfield Shopping Center.  See my review for that as well.  In closing, is a pleasant, picturesque location in the middle of the city that's worth a stop for the travelers to our city.< /Text><pics>None</pics><resp>None< /resp>< gmapID>

< Review>
Multiplex theaters with big, comfy reclining seats. Kiosks for ticket purchases (including MoviePass) are much faster than waiting in line at the ticket window. There's often a long line to enter the theater area - they need more ticket-takers. For a fun treat, get some coffee or tea from the CafeX robot on the Metreon ground floor. There's also an automatic ramen machine. The ramen isn't bad, but a bit overpriced for what it is.<//Review>

<userid>112789599462886764793<//userid><username>Grace Park< /username>< time>

<Rating>4<//Rating>< review>
The mall has a few big names that are solid (target, starbucks, chipotle, the movie theater, super duper burgers) but theyre all things that you can find elsewhere and would come for even if it weren't in this mall.
The mall besides the things i listed, dont offer too many other things. Their food court is widespread and doesnt surprise anyone with the food quality, and you always see restaurants going out of business and coming back in.
But this mall also had the robot coffee (cafex) for novelty, offers free wifi, connected to yerba buena park, and is maintained very well! Not really a shopping mall as much as a place you can hang out.<//review>

<username>XANE Michael Scott Hackamack<//username><date>1522432204638</date><Rating>5< /Rating>< text>
The Metreon is a ULTRA MODERN shoping complex with the Yerba Buena Garden Waterfalls & Park just outside on the inner side...and the convince of one stop shopping & entertainment within!
The City Target is the most reasonable food store in San Francisco...along with all the rest Target offers at incredibly LOW prices!
The Metreon Theaters have the IMAX option for many of the newest & latest show offerings.
The Restraunts & Boutique eateries offer all types of fare for nearly evert taste.
You can buy socks, meet your date, catch the latest film, and stroll the park afterward.
Its a MUST SEE when in San Francisco!< /text>

Try to go see your movie in a Dolby Cinema theatre if you can. The experience rivals the Imax. Seats are super comphy padded recliners that shake during appropriate moments in the movie. Super fun. < text>
AMC Metreon is my go-to place for movies, and the foodstuffs and Target and other stuff in the area are a nice touch. I've been to a bunch of the restaurants in the food court, most recently ShareTea (boba tea) and Moolicious (crepes), though I almost never come here solely for the food. Metreon is in a convenient location that's easy to get to from downtown by transit, car, walking, whatever. Plus, since its backyard is Yerba Buena, there are oftentimes festivals and other events going on.< /text>

< Text>
Ah the old place of the dead sony failed mall project. I heard this used to be a giant tilt arcade.. i love arcades! too bad its gone. Now this expensive metreon is here that doesn't even play every movie! Usually you can just go across the street to the westfield theater and catch a movie you cant find here. Theres tons of new restaurants that opened in the same shopping center. But I think the 2 best things about this place is the opening of the chipotle and the chronicle books store. Movies here are expensive but then again they are expensive in general. Its nice to get a coffee and sit in the park outside.</Text>

100317833931102218342< /userid>
< Response>
None</Response>
<name>Daivat Dholakia< /name><time>1411708122777<//time>< text>
This place transformed from a Theater off Yerba Beuna to an amazing space for shopping, movies, food + much more.

Few years back, I wouldn't have noticed Metreon as some place I would visit occasionally but after renovations and upgrades, I see myself going here quite often. On the 1st floor you have got a ton of eating options from Chipotle, La Boulange, Starbucks (hey you get real food there now), a whole food court, Cako, Froyo, pretty much whatever you want. They also have a couple of stores off 4th street including an apparel shop, book store etc.

2nd Floor has got the Citys *only* Target store. The floors above are occupied by AMC including an IMAX theater (the only real IMAX in the city).

If you are looking for parking, there is none at Metreon but there is a parking lot right across the street called Mission Parking. Public transport is easily available within a couple of blocks and since this location is in Downtown, its difficult to miss.<//text>
<rating>5<//rating></record>

1342555659180< /Time>
< Rate>
4< /Rate>
<review>This is the official Shiftee co-work space.  Decent wi-fi, nice facilities, plenty of power, and a bevy of food options.  Even during lunch there are plenty of places to seat, and a ton of opportunities to network with other people working here.  At least a wash financially compared to other co-work spaces in SF, and here for that price you also get some great eats.

If you are a small team(1-3), this is totally a great deal.  Plus, you can always catch a movie at the great theatre upstairs after work.  The only things I would change:

- An option to pay some amount($10/mo?) for better Wi-Fi.
- An app or website to order food and have it brought to table(hate to have to leave computers, etc alone while getting food).

I have some very small concerns on what will happen to this atmosphere when the Target opens in 2013, but I believe the management company will be able to handle it.<//review>< pics>
None</pics>
